# *Primary Key vs Foreign Key*

- Each of these tables has a column that uniquely identifies each row of that table. These are called primary keys:
    - `order_id`Â forÂ `orders`
    - `subscription_id`Â forÂ `subscriptions`
    - `customer_id`Â forÂ `customers`
- Primary keys have a few requirements:
    - None of the values can beÂ `NULL`.
    - Each value must be unique (i.e., you canâ€™t have two customers with the sameÂ `customer_id`Â in theÂ `customers`Â table).
    - A table cannot have more than one primary key column.
- When the primary key for one table appears in a different table, it is called a foreign key.

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/1e11bafd-5245-4e93-9898-2c6e41d5cc3a/Untitled.png)

- `customer_id`Â (the primary key forÂ `customers`) andÂ `subscription_id`Â (the primary key forÂ `subscriptions`) both appear in this.
- SoÂ `customer_id`Â is a primary key when it appears inÂ `customers`, but a foreign key when it appears inÂ `orders`.

